## Dark-mode via system preference (no JS)

Bulma 1.0 uses CSS custom properties and defines dark-mode tokens under a [data-theme="dark"] selector. Two no-JS paths to follow the OS preference:

1. Inline CSS shim — add a small @media block that copies Bulma dark tokens when prefers-color-scheme is dark:

       @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
         :root:not([data-theme="light"]) {
           --bulma-scheme-main: hsl(221, 14%, 10%);
           --bulma-text: hsl(221, 14%, 86%);
           /* ... a handful more ... */
         }
       }

   Keep the list small — we only need to override the tokens our pages actually reference.

2. Drop-in extension — import a one-file community CSS that aliases prefers-color-scheme: dark to Bulma data-theme="dark" tokens. Faster if one has settled on being maintained.

Start with approach 1 (zero extra dep). Revisit if the hand-written token list grows past ~15 rules.

## Optional follow-on: user-controllable toggle

If we later want an explicit light/dark/auto selector that survives the system preference:

- Add a cookie read in parse-query/handle handlers in src/cch/server.clj
- Emit <html data-theme="..."> in the hiccup head based on the cookie
- Toggle UI: three form-post buttons (light/dark/auto), server writes cookie, 303 back

Still no client JS. Not in scope for 5mn unless specifically asked.
